sumInfo <- Go_sumInfo(
Prep_overview = "A total of 79 samples were DNA-extracted and prepared for sequencing. All samples were successfully extracted and prepared for library construction; however, one sample (S_180103_00090, MIRA) failed during sequencing. Except for this sample, all others reached a plateau in the rarefaction curve and were therefore included in downstream analyses, resulting in a final dataset of 78 samples (3 Control, 53 MIRA, and 22 LUPUS). Given the low number of control, only discrivig in taxanomic barplot, and excluded alpha, beta, and DA test avoid over interpreat",
Taxa_overview = "The relative abundance bar plot shows variability in microbial composition across individual samples and treatment groups. Across the MIRA, LUPUS, and control groups, several samples were dominated by taxa within the Lachnospiraceae and Ruminococcaceae families, including Faecalibacterium prausnitzii, Agathobacter rectalis, Blautia spp., and Ruminococcus spp. Additional contributions were observed from taxa such as Bacteroides vulgatus, Bacteroides uniformis, Bifidobacterium spp., and Akkermansia muciniphila. Overall, the dominant taxa varied between samples, indicating heterogeneous microbial community structures across individuals and treatment groups.",
Alpha_div = "Alpha diversity was assessed using Chao1 richness and Shannon diversity indices. Both indices showed slightly higher values in the MIRA group compared with the LUPUS group; however, the differences were not statistically significant (Chao1: p = 0.084; Shannon: p = 0.35, Wilcoxon test).",
Beta_div = "Beta diversity was evaluated using Bray–Curtis, unweighted UniFrac, and weighted UniFrac distance metrics and visualized using principal coordinates analysis (PCoA). Samples from the MIRA and LUPUS groups showed largely overlapping distributions across the ordination plots. PERMANOVA analysis revealed significant differences in microbial community composition between the groups for Bray–Curtis and unweighted UniFrac distances, but not for weighted UniFrac (Bray–Curtis: R² = 0.024, p = 0.004; unweighted UniFrac: R² = 0.024, p = 0.002; weighted UniFrac: R² = 0.011, p = 0.493).",
Bacterial_div = NA,
DA_test = "Differential abundance analysis was performed using DESeq2, ALDEx2, and ANCOM-BC2. Several taxa showed nominally significant differences between the MIRA and LUPUS groups (p < 0.05). DESeq2 identified Lachnoclostridium and Akkermansia muciniphila as enriched in the MIRA group and Coprococcus eutactus in the LUPUS group. ALDEx2 suggested additional taxa differing between groups, including members of the Lachnospiraceae and Ruminococcaceae families such as Roseburia intestinalis, Blautia faecis, and Faecalibacterium duncaniae enriched in the MIRA group and taxa including Bifidobacterium adolescentis and Streptococcus spp. enriched in the LUPUS group based on nominal p-values. However, none of the taxa identified by ALDEx2 remained significant after FDR correction. ANCOM-BC2 detected multiple taxa differing between groups, including enrichment of *Roseburia intestinalis, Bacteroides vulgatus,* and *Ruminococcus bromii* in the MIRA group and *Bifidobacterium spp., Streptococcus spp.*, and members of the *Ruminococcus gnavus* group in the LUPUS group.",
Summary = NA,
Conclusion = "Overall, only one sample failed during sequencing. The exclusion of this sample is unlikely to affect the overall statistical analysis, although the cause of the failure is currently under investigation.
The data provide an overview of the microbial community structure in this cohort. Alpha diversity showed a tendency toward higher values in the MIRA group, although the differences were not statistically significant. Beta diversity analyses revealed substantial overlap in microbial community composition between the MIRA and LUPUS groups, with modest but significant differences observed for Bray–Curtis and unweighted UniFrac distances. Differential abundance analyses suggested potential differences in several taxa, including members of the Lachnospiraceae lineage; however, consistent microbial signatures were not observed across analytical methods. Notably, previous studies have reported that gut microbiota dysbiosis in systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE) shows substantial heterogeneity across cohorts. These findings therefore provide an initial characterization of the stool microbiome in this cohort and are broadly consistent with previous reports describing heterogeneous microbiome alterations in SLE.",
Useful_info = "Silverman et al., Nature Reviews Rheumatology, 2023 The gut microbiome in systemic lupus erythematosus: lessons from rheumatic fever [click here]https://www.nature.com/articles/s41584-023-01071-8",
)
